You can create a [custom DSL](https://docs.spring.io/spring-security/reference/servlet/configuration/java.html#jc-custom-dsls). This is actually how Spring Security works internally.

```java
public class MyCustomDsl extends AbstractHttpConfigurer&lt;MyCustomDsl, HttpSecurity&gt; {
	@Override
	public void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
		AuthenticationManager authenticationManager = http.getSharedObject(AuthenticationManager.class);
		http.addFilterBefore(new MyAuthenticationFilter(authenticationManager), UsernamePasswordAuthenticationFilter.class);
	}

	public static MyCustomDsl customDsl() {
		return new MyCustomDsl();
	}
}
```

Then you can apply the custom DSL when building the `SecurityFilterChain`:
```java
@Bean
public SecurityFilterChain filterChain(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
	// ...
	http.apply(customDsl());
	return http.build();
}
```

If you want to inject AuthenticationManager into other spring components, you can use the following configuration.

    @Bean
    public AuthenticationManager authenticationManager(AuthenticationConfiguration authenticationConfiguration) throws Exception {
         return authenticationConfiguration.getAuthenticationManager();
    }

